      <a href="https://orangette.net/2008/07/a-bold-statement/#comment-10531"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2013-12-08T02:04:03-05:00">Sunday, December 8, 2013 at 2:04 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Help! What changes should I make for high altitude baking (6,000 feet)?  I tried the recipe as printed and my cookies were flat &#8211; delicious &#8211; but flat. Also, do you recommend convection oven cooking? Please answer as I&#39;d like to make them again!<br />Thanks,<br />Carol in Sun Valley, Idaho</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-10529" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/01493708300940204826" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Molly</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2008/07/a-bold-statement/#comment-10529"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2013-12-08T06:40:15-05:00">Sunday, December 8, 2013 at 6:40 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Carol! I wish I knew what to tell you, but I sadly know nothing about baking at high altitude.  I am useless!  If I were you, I would do a Google search for some high altitude baking tips or a high altitude chocolate chip cookie recipe to see how it differs from this one. But as for the convection question, I can indeed tell you that yes, I do like the way these cookies turn out with convection.  I&#39;ve baked them in both convection and conventional ovens, and they work in both.</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
